rename.to: [Documentation] How to register custom operator in onnxruntime

body:
> The built directory is not generating any shared object which can be loaded by register_custom_ops_library(<path_to_object_file>) of SessionOptions

Is there a specific error message you're getting?

> > The built directory is not generating any shared object which can be loaded by register_custom_ops_library(<path_to_object_file>) of SessionOptions
> 
> Is there a specific error message you're getting?

As the shared object is not being generated I can't post any error message regarding that but I have posted an error message when i am trying to run the inference of the custom operator in python's onnxruntime. Do you have any idea on how to register a custom operator written in C++ Api in python's onnxruntime?

The tutorial seems to be setup so with the custom op implementation being built into an executable along with ORT, so it's used directly instead of by registering a separate library. To create a standalone library the cmake setup would need to be changed, and you'd need to call RegisterCustomOpsLibrary like [this](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/1e34440c370d40085fad5fd1b1002b4a04c5991d/onnxruntime/test/shared_lib/test_inference.cc#L122-L125 ) example.

That probably won't fix anything if you're currently adding an Ort::CustomOpDomain instance to the SessionOptions.

> com.microsoft:Reduction_dd

Make sure the domain string and op name match exactly. I would not recommend using the existing 'com.microsoft' domain though - for a custom op it's safer to use a custom domain name so there's no potential clash with existing things.

issue.title: WIP [Documentation]: C# Workflow for consuming "Augmented" Onnx model with Custom Operators

labels.name: documentation
labels.description: improvements or additions to documentation; typically submitted using template

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

body:
@skottmckay 
Yes I have made sure the domain string and op name match exactly and I have already tried with different domain name than "com.microsoft" and still I get the same error. As per the link you have provided i have followed the 1st approach and already have tested the inference. 
As you have mentioned to make changes in the cmake file. I am able to generate an .so file by add_library() in CMakeList.txt.
Now when I am trying to load this shared object in  Python's onnxruntime via ```session_options = ort.SessionOptions()
session_options.register_custom_ops_library("libcustomop.so")```.
i get the following error:
```
Fail: [ONNXRuntimeError] : 1 : FAIL : Failed to get symbol RegisterCustomOps with error: .../bin/python: undefined symbol: RegisterCustomOps
```
Even if I pass an empty string in sessions.options.register_custom_ops_library("") the same error persists.

If it fails to get the symbol that would imply the library is not exporting it correctly. ORT will load the shared library and do symbol lookup using `dlsym`. Can you check what is exported? e.g. https://www.baeldung.com/linux/shared-library-exported-functions

I believe an empty string is doing the same due to how linux behaves. dlopen with an empty string returns the handle for the main program, which also won't have a RegisterCustomOps symbol exported. We could explicitly check for an empty string and provide a better error though.

@skottmckay Thank you for your help. I realized I was not exporting anything in my code and that was the root cause of the problem. Everything works now and I can successfully run the session in python's onnxruntime.

issue.title: [Feature Request: c#] Provide Onnxruntime related Nugets consisting of contributed Operators as shared library

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
### Describe the feature request

- We now have improved [documentation ](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/12896)on how to consume (through registration) custom operators which is relevant to c# users
- There is a new effort in [refactoring the c and c++ API](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/12998) for dealing with custom operators, which I hope will be relevant to this feature request.

It is time we consider how to provide different Onnxruntime related NuGets which consist of shared libraries that expose [contributed operators](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/docs/ContribOperators.md) similar in format to [custom_op_library.dll](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/2f9b358d16885c8330eaa34a932315e3b176082c/csharp/test/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Tests.NetCoreApp/InferenceTest.netcore.cs#L634) and therefore accessible to c# users


### Describe scenario use cases

[Reference](https://github.com/dotnet/TorchSharp/discussions/526)

#### use case 1
- [ ] Evaluate the feasibility to use TorchSharp to integrate custom operators and export to ONNX.
- [ ] Use ML.NET to register the integrated custom operators used in the exported ONNX model before consuming the ONNX model

#### use case 2
- [ ] Instead of integrating custom operators as stated in use case 1, integrate existing contributed operators distributed by ONNXRUNTIME
- [ ] Use ML.NET to register the integrated contributed operators used in the exported ONNX model before consuming the ONNX model
